                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d508">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.113/306: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Child</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-07-12T13:00:00+01:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 12, 1922—1 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received July 12—1:58 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>110. Your 94, June 29, 3 p.m. Note just received from the Foreign Office states
                    that the Italian Government having ordered that no sale Italian arms and
                    munitions should occur in China, either to Chinese buyers or through their
                    intermediaries of whatsoever nationality <pb facs="0855" n="735" xml:id="pg_735"
                    /> until the reestablishment in China of normal conditions with a single
                    government, it experiences no difficulty in extending such declaration to apply
                    also to the importation of arms, munitions and accessories in China including
                    the various settlements and concessions therein.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Child</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
